Use ReflectionOnlyLoad() in the remote proxy reference prober
Moves IsReferencing() to AssemblyExtensions

Fixes the assemby loading into the temp AppDomain

As specified by MSDN, AppDomain.Load() is just a convenience method for
Assembly.Load(). This means that the previous behavior loaded all the
assemblies into both the inspection AppDomain and AppDomain.Current, when
the code intent was clear that this was not desired.

However, if the assembly is passed between AppDomains, because it is not
serializable, it would be loaded as well into both AppDomains, therefore
the solution is to make a proxy prober which loads the assembly in the
inspection domain and locally determines if the desired reference exists.
Unit test for detection of loaded assemblies

Added ISerializerFactory + implementation

The idea is that this what you will take a dependency on, instead of
IEnumerable<ISerializer>, and it will give you the serializer that
matches the provided MediaRange.

The default implementation will take the default serializers into
account and only return them if no other match could be made.

If there are multiple matched (not counting the defaults) then it will
throw an InvalidOperationException with a detailed error message, telling
you about the types of the implementaions that it matched.

I have also updated the ISerializer.CanSerialize and Serialize methods
to accept a MediaRange instance, instead of string, for the contentType
parameter. This works fine since it can implicitly be case to/from a
string.

Merge pull request #2013 from xt0rted/patch-6

Remove old reference
Remove old reference

Perform case-insensitive lookups in EmbeddedFileResource

Previously, `EmbeddedFileResource` was overly picky with regards to
embedded resource name casing. Particularly, this was causing problems
when `AddDirectory()` on `EmbeddedStaticContentConventionBuilder` was
given an incorrectly-capitalized `contentPath` argument, i.e.:

  _.AddDirectory("content", GetType().Assembly, contentPath: "content"));

Provided that embedded resources were under "Foo.Content", all requests
to `/content/...` would fail.

With this patch, `EmbeddedFileResource` becomes much less picky
about casing, which it was all along nevertheless except for a
couple places.

Perform case-insensitive replacement in EmbeddedFileResponse

Everywhere else in `EmbeddedFileResponse` string operations are
performed with `OrdinalIgnoreCase` flag. This was the only place
where casing was not ignored.

Allow overriding contentPath in Embedded fixture

Allow tests to override the value passed to `AddDirectory()`

Rename parameter in Embedded-related fixture

Previously, `GetEmbeddedStaticContent()` had had an unused
`root` parameter. Rename it to `contentPath,` which, I think,
is more appropriate.

Runtime view updating still broken though - seems to be a Spark
problem - I can see the updated view being sent to Spark from
NancyViewFolder.UpdateContents, and I can see the lats modified time

doesn't play nicely with anything else, so currently it just
grabs all the discovered views on startup and uses those. This
means that runtime view discovery is never going to be honored.

although I'm not 100% sure why as yet.

Introduced BindingConfigs

The IBinder.Bind method now accepts a BindingConfi instance that
contains information for the binder on how it is expected to
behave during binding. Additionally the Bind(), Bind<>() and BindTo()
extensions enables you to pass this in.

Currently the only piece of configuration that is in the BindingConfig
type is to control whether or not the binder should be allowed to
overwrite properties that doesn't have default(T) as its value.

Additionally there are two static members on it called Default and
AllowOverride. The latter returns an instance of BindingConfig with
Override set to true.

Added support for route descriptions

RouteDescriptions got a Description property that is set by the
RouteCache at application startup. The cache uses the new
IRouteDescriptionProvider interface to get the description.

The default implementation of the IRouteDescriptionProvider looks
for the descriptions in resource files. If you create a resource
file, with the same name as the module that has the route(s) you
want to add descriptions for, and use the route path as the key
then it will automatically be picked up. Note that you have to set
your resource as "no code behind" in order to use paths as resource
keys

You can swap out the IRouteDescriptionProvider, for your own one,
in the internal configuration. This enables you to store the
descriptions anywhere!

field TestAssemblySuffixes on ConfigurableBoostrapper.

Updated tests to comply with dynamic return type

A couple of tests that explicitly invoked a Route and asserted
on the return. There was also a case where an implicit cast, from
null to Response, could happen inside the route action, before it
was invoked.

Returning null from a route or returning "foo.bar" where bar is null
causes different behaviors in C# when the return type has an implicit
cast operator that can be applied. With the change to dynamic return,
it will always return a proper null, thus some tests needed to be
setup differently

Converted action return type to dynamic

This is the first step to introducing content negotiation. This change
will enable us to return any object from the route action and have
Nancy figure out what it should do based on the type of the returned
value.

Changed auto registration behavior

The DisableAutoRegistration function on the ConfigurableBootstrapper
has been replaced by EnableAutoRegistration. This means that with this
patch, the auto-registration will be disabled by default instead of
enabled. The reason for this are primarily for performance but also
to help make tests be more implicit in setting up the context in
which they execute.

Updated modulePath based conventions

They will not return an empty string if the modulepath is null or
empty. When a convention returns an empty string then the convention
is ignored by the DefaultViewResolver and the next convention is
invoked instead

Made RequestHeaders writeable

You can now change the value of the request headers. If you assign a header
the default value of the return type (for instance null for a string) then
the header will be removed from the keys collection until a new value is

and added a test that ensures the registrations are preformed before the

Split IStartup into two interfaces

The IStartup interface was removed and replaced by two new interfaces
called IApplicationStartup and IApplicationRegistrations. The former
lets you run code on application startup and the latter lets you register
stuff into the container at application startup. The registrations are
performed before the startups

THIS IS A BREAKING CHANGE

Updated view location convention order

The conventions will now use the most strict convention first and
work its way back to the less strict one. The new order is

  - views/modulepath/viewname
  - views/modulename/viewname
  - modulepath/viewname
  - modulename/viewname
  - views/viewname
  - viewname

This is a breaking change!

Disposing body stream at end of request

The NancyContext will now dispose the Request, when done, which in turn
will dispose the Body stream (RequestStream instance). If the stream has
been switched to a new stream (memory or file) then that stream will also
be disposed. If the stream has been switched to the filesystem then the
temporary file is attempted to be deleted as well, so we do not leave
any garbage files around.

Gave DynamicDictionary and DynamicDictionaryValue some love. The dictionary will now *always* return a DynamicDictionaryValue instance, even if there is no value with the name that was invoked (works for both direct member access and with the indexer). The value will have a null-value. You can now use the HasValue property on a value to see if its null or not like Request.Query.Foo.HasValue and you can also use the == and != equality operator

Split RouteResolver into two intefaces. The IRoutePatternMatcher is used to determine if the requested uri is a match for any of the routes in the routecache, i.e its the thing that understands route pattern syntaxes.. replace it to use a custom syntax..the IRouteResolver now uses the pattern matcher to figure out which routes that match the request and then decides which of the possible matches that should be choosen... also added so that it will return a 405 (Method Not Allowed) response if there were route path matches but not for the request method that was sent in

Worked around the Ninject child container limitation by also registering the modules into the child container when it's constructed.
